segments.text: Now, I think this machine is for work.
Well, after you left this ranch, did you come here immediately?
No, my husband was working here with the Hawaiinan.
What is it called now?
The Hawaiinan?
The Hawaiinan, yes.
Well, he had a ranch with the lady.
with Maria McEmbra, a teacher.
Yes.
That's what she worked with.
She worked with my father.
She also sowed.
Yes.
Because she wanted them to work on the land they had.
It wasn't much, but they worked on it.
Yes.
My father worked on it and sowed it.
He sowed corn, beans, whatever he sowed, he gave it to him.
Yes.
That's why I told him, I said, I don't want half of it, Juan, I don't want it.
All I want is for you to work for my land, because I want my land to be worked for, so that they don't take it away from us, sell it to us.
And they said, well, when you do what you do, come.
And I said, yes.
They came and brought pumpkins, eggplants, candy, everything my father planted, they came and brought it.
My father went and said, there's this and that, because they're going to bring it.
I used to take care of a kid who had to go to school.
And there was a lot of corn.
When we came from Kelaren, we packed up and went to Rancho Uribe.
And that's where we went to work.
To unload, to chop, to wet the land.
Before you came here to Mexico during the war, can you tell us something about the war?
Why is there a war in Mexico?
I don't know.
No, I don't know.
My father never told us that.
No?
Never?
No, he never told us why.
Well, it's just that the war was done, as it's done here, by any Chucutani.
That's how the war was done in Mexico.
I don't know with whom they fought in Mexico.
I don't know much about that.
It's just that that year was when they came here.
They came here to Matamoros, and from there they went here.
Yes.
Since then, we've never...
I didn't know about Mexico until they died.
My father and my mother died.
Because they didn't know that my aunt was in Matamoros, on the other side of Brandeis.
And I was a little sad because my mother and my father died.
And because I didn't know so much, they said that they were going to take me there.
And my aunt came and we lived there.
Well, this war was called the Revolution.
The Mexican Revolution.
Was it a good thing for Mexico or not?
I don't know.
No?
I don't know.
Your mom or dad never said... No, they... Well, they talked to other gentlemen.
Yes.
But we didn't pay much attention because they...
Well, I don't know.
My father and my mother had those customs.
When they came to talk, they were the only ones there.
We were the ones in charge of the kitchen.
And they talked to the men and women in the kitchen.
When my mother came to talk to the women, to visit them,
They were talking to each other and we were in the kitchen cooking and it was almost noon.
When the food was ready, we would talk to my mother and my aunt.
When the girls came to visit us, they would go to the kitchen with my aunt and my mother and we would talk to the girls.
And they would prepare the food for us.
When it was ready, they would bring their girls to eat and we would eat.
They were the neighbors.
Before they weren't.
And now the boys know everything because they hear everything and they listen to everything first than the older ones.
We weren't.
We were the most different people before.
They weren't like they were.
The parents were very reserved.
They talked to the people who came to visit them.
The ladies too.
And now the boys realize everything, the conversations of the parents or other people.
And we didn't.
My parents were raised differently and we were raised like them.
Other models, not like now.
But the models are very different.
Well, your mother had sadness for Mexico.
Yes, she said it was her homeland and everything, but here it is, here are my children, here is my family.
My mother died, my brothers.
What am I going to do in Mexico?
Her mother's siblings were in Mexico.
Yes, but they died.
Her mother and her two siblings died.
Only her little sister lives in Mexico.
She lives in Padilla, Tamaulipas.
That's my mother's little sister.
Her name is Edelmira Balboa.
The governor of Tamaulipas
Prageres Balboa.
I didn't hear him say it.
I didn't hear him say it.
Prageres Balboa, who was the governor of Texas, who is... What's his name?
Do you know what the governor of Texas is called?
Well, I understand.
Yeah, but I forgot his name.
Well, just like the governor of Texas, in the United States.
Yes.
That man, Rajerez Balboa, is my aunt's brother, my mother's little sister.
Your aunt's brother and governor?
Yes, he was governor from Tamaulipas to Matamoros, because it's Tamaulipas to Matamoros, right?
Yes.
Texas, the capital of Texas is Austin, Texas.
And the capital of Tamaulipas is Ciudad Victoria, up to Matamoros.
Well, he was governor from Ciudad Victoria to Matamoros, my uncle.
He's my aunt's little brother.
In what year was he governor?
Last year he was.
Now I don't know who was the governor of the state of Tamaulipas.
He was the governor of Tamaulipas.
He was the governor of Tamaulipas.
And he is the brother of his aunt?
My uncle's brother.
Your uncle's brother.
Is he your uncle?

Yes, he's my uncle because my mother... My mother's sister is... She's my mother's mother's daughter, but she didn't... My mother had another relative, because her father was another, and then my grandmother became a widow and married that man.
And my aunt was born.
Yes.
And he had a lot of education.
My aunt?
Yes.
My aunt from Elmira?
Yes.
Oh, yes.
She had school in Mexico.
Yes.
She had school in Mexico.
In Mexico, I have a nephew.
He's a nephew because his mother is my first sister.
He's the daughter of a sister of my father, sister of my father.
And the boy?
He is the son of my cousin, and he is a public servant.
He is a very unintelligent man, the boy.
And he took me out about a month ago.
He took out my baptismal certificate.
Yes.
Because I didn't have it, and I needed that paper.
Why didn't I have faith in baptism?
Because I was baptized when I was very little and my father came to Mexico, to the United States, and they never gave me faith in baptism.
Because at that time they didn't give faith in baptism, only that all the records remained in the church where the children were baptized.
Because there were no fathers like here, standing up.
They came from other big towns to do baptism, to baptize children.
Every two years my mother and every third year they came to baptize.
And when I was born, it was the time when I was coming from the father to baptize.
And it was when they baptized me.
But there were papers in Padil, in Padil's church.
Well, I think this machine is better, because the other machine had a problem.
His uncle, his name was Balboa, Mr. Balboa, who was governor.
Yes, like two years ago, I don't know.
And his family?
I don't know his family.
When we went, my uncle said that my uncle, when he was announced and came to Nuevo Laredo,
When the governor of Texas came.
Ah, yes.
I heard him say that the governor of Tamaulipas was going to come.
And he was from a rich family, or poor, or middle-aged?
I don't know.
No, his father was the administrator of the hacienda.
Ah, from Hacienda de Dolores.
His father was an administrator.
He was the administrator of the farm.
Yes, yes.
Well, in Mexico, as humble as a family is, what makes it
to be introduced among other people who know about it.
Because of their language, right?
Yes.
Because of their education.
Yes.
That boy is very humble.
Yes.
His father was a worker at a ranch.
He was a cowherd, as they say here in Caboes.
Yes.
His father.
His father.
The boy's father.
But his father died as a result of that.
They were raising a lot of cattle.
A lot of cattle.
And they came over him and a very brave bull came over him.
He went over him, over the horse and he hit him.
He was very bad.
His father died.
They stayed there for half a year.
His mother had them in school and he graduated from school.
And my aunt said,
He was a very polite boy.
He was very simple, but he had a very good education.
Ah, yes.
And this is the most important thing in Mexico.
Education.
Education.
Is it the same here?
What?
Education.
Education.
Is it the most important thing here?
I think so.
The opportunity.
For work.
Yes.
And in Mexico too.
He is a boy who has a lot of intelligence, he has a very good memory.
He will soon finish his school.
I have a nephew here.
He is the youngest of my brothers.
He graduated from school in May.
He has very good, how do you say?
l tiene muy buenos grados y muy inteligente en la escuela.
S.
Y l tiene plan de, ya tiene todo arreglado porque l quiere ir al colegio.
S.
Quiere ir al colegio.
Y nada menos ayer le habl el sargento porque lo que dice que tiene muy buenos requisitos.
S.
De los marines.
Quieren llevrselo.
S.
Porque dice que tiene un muchachito muy guay.
who has a lot of intelligence in studying and everything.
And he said he had a plan.
He asked other people, what plans do you have?
I have a plan to go to college.
Yes.
Well, he says, we'll give you college.
We'll give you training and we'll give you everything.
Yes.
But who knows what he's going to do.
He wants to go to college.
Yes.
He's curious.
And he just turned 18.
He graduated from school and now he has plans to spend the rest of his life on alcohol.
